Stacks

Stacks

  • Recall the stack of newspapers?

  • Used to implement a last-in first-out (LIFO) type protocol

Stack

  • A stack is a linear data structure

  • Access limited to a last-in first-out order.

  • Adding and removing items is restricted to one end known as the top of the stack.

  • An empty stack contains no items.

Stack and operations

  • $\tt Stack(\;)$ : Creates a new empty stack.

  • $\tt isEmpty(\;)$ : Returns a boolean value indicating if the stack is empty.

  • $\tt length(\;)$ : Returns the number of items in the stack.

  • $\tt pop(\;)$ : Removes and returns the top item of the stack

    • if the stack is not empty.
    • items cannot be popped from an empty stack.
    • The next item on the stack becomes the new top item.

Stack and operations...

  • $\tt peek(\;)$ : Returns a reference to the item on top of a non-empty stack without removing it.

    • Peeking, which cannot be done on an empty stack, does not modify the stack contents.

  • $\tt push(item)$ : Adds the given item to the top of the stack.

In[2]:
# Implementation of the Stack ADT using a Python list.
class Stack :

    # Creates an empty stack.
    def __init__( self ): 
        self._theItems = list()

    # Returns True if the stack is empty or False otherwise.
    def isEmpty( self ): 
        return len( self ) == 0

    # Returns the number of items in the stack.
    def __len__ ( self ):
        return len( self._theItems )

    # Returns the top item on the stack without removing it.
    def peek( self ):
        assert not self.isEmpty(), "Cannot peek at an empty stack" 
        return self._theItems[-1]

    # Removes and returns the top item on the stack.
    def pop( self ):
        assert not self.isEmpty(), "Cannot pop from an empty stack" 
        return self._theItems.pop()

    # Push an item onto the top of the stack.
    def push( self, item ): 
        self._theItems.append( item )

# Implementation of the Stack ADT using a singly linked list.
class Stack :

    # Creates an empty stack.
    def __init__( self ): 
        self._top = None 
        self._size = 0
    
    # Returns True if the stack is empty or False otherwise.
    def isEmpty( self ): 
        return self._top is None
    
    # Returns the number of items in the stack.
    def __len__( self ): 
        return self._size

    # Returns the top item on the stack without removing it.
    def peek( self ):
        assert not self.isEmpty(), "Cannot peek at an empty stack" 
        return self._top.item
    
    # Removes and returns the top item on the stack.
    def pop( self ):
        assert not self.isEmpty(), "Cannot pop from an empty stack" 
        node = self._top
        self._top = self._top.next
        self._size -= 1
        return node.item
    
    # Pushes an item onto the top of the stack.
    def push( self, item ) :
        self._top = _StackNode( item, self._top ) 
        print("top is -->",item,self._top)
        self._size += 1
        
# The private storage class for creating stack nodes.
class _StackNode :
    def __init__( self, item, link ) :
        print(item,"points to:",link)
        self.item = item
        self.next = link

Pop Operation

Applications of Stacks - 1

  • Balanced parenthesis ( ), brackets [ ], braces { }

  • Basic Idea:

    • push opening ones into a stack and pop them when you see matching closing ones.

  • For example,

    • "[ 1 + (3 - 5) ]"
      • push '[' into the stack
      • push '(' into the stack
      • when we see ')' , match and pop from the stack
      • when we see ']' , match and pop from the stack

Applications of Stacks - 2

  • Evaluating Postfix Expressions

  • Infix Expression: (A + B - C)

  • Postfix Expression: AB+C-

    • (operand operand operator)

  • Prefix Expression: -+ABC

    • (operator operand operand)

Postfix Expression: ABC+*D/

- (B + C)
- A * (B + C) 
- (A * (B + C)) / D

Example with parentheses

Note that the order of the operands never changes! :-)

Evaluating a postfix expression

A B C + * D /

A=8 C=3 B=2 D=4

Evaluating a postfix expression

A B C + * D /

A=8 C=3 B=2 D=4

  • Stack: 3 2 8 Looking at: +
    • (2 + 3)
  • Stack: 5 8 Looking at: *
    • (8 * 5)
  • Stack: 4 40 Looking at: /
    • (40 / 4)
  • Stack: 10

Applications of Stacks - 3

  • Convert Infix Expressions to Postfix

Convert Infix Expressions to Postfix

Input: A fully parenthesised infix expression

Output: The postfix equivalent

  • If you see an operand, output it.

  • If you see an operator, push it on the stack.

  • If you see an opening parenthesis, push it on the stack.

  • If you see a closing parenthesis, pop the operator and write it.

((A * B) + (C / D))

  • Stack : ( ( *
  • output: A B
  • symbol: )

((A * B) + (C / D))

  • Stack : (
  • output: A B *
  • Stack : ( + ( /
  • output: A B * C D
  • symbol: )

((A * B) + (C / D))

  • Stack : ( +
  • output: A B * C D /
  • symbol: )
  • Stack :
  • output: A B * C D / +
  • symbol:

for i in range( 17 ) :
    #print(i)
    if i % 3 == 0 : 
        values.push( i )
        print(" - pushing",i)
    elif i % 4 == 0 : 
        print(" - popping",values.pop())
